\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/nf.absolute_value}{Absolute value of a field}}
\begin{definition*}\label{nf.absolute_value}
\uses{}
An \textbf{absolute value} of a field $k$ is a function $|\ |:k\to \R_{\ge 0}$ that satisfies:

\begin{itemize}
\item  $|x|=0$ if and only if $x=0$;
\item  $|xy| = |x||y|$;
\item  $|x+y| \le |x|+|y|$.
\end{itemize}

Absolute values that satisfy the stronger condition $|x+y|\le \max(|x|,|y|)$ are \textbf{nonarchimedean}, while those that do not are \textbf{archimedean}; the latter arise only in fields of characteristic zero.  The \textbf{trivial absolute value} assigns 1 to every nonzero element of $k$; it is a nonarchimedean absolute value.

Absolute values $|\ |_1$ and $|\ |_2$ are \textbf{equivalent} if there exists a positive real number $c$ such that $|x|_1 = |x|_2^c$ for all $x\in k$; this defines an equivalence relation on the set of absolute values of $k$.
\end{definition*}


